1. The only thing I did with my life while writing “All The Black Girls Are Activists” was Watch Harry Potter full series several times and read romance novels.
2. This was my activism because I was cultivating a life of frivolity that nobody is coming to give me without my own resistance.
3. But I decided in 2019 that I wanted a life where my resistance didn’t have to kill me. Which is when I launched #DreamYourselfFree because I want to create from “saw things I imagined” not from “weary of the ways of the world.”
4. Those are two different points of creation and Blk girls deserve “saw things I imagined” creation.
5. My publisher @rowhousepub HAD to have seen me on social media talking abt romance novels and Harry Potter and yet… when I needed a cute little extension on my first chapter deadlines — with EASE @bexlife was like, “Girl… send me the book when you get back in your body”
6. B/c they know the goal of my book is soft, seated, while, well, playful, in joy, easeful black Women — and THAT place is our very worthy and credible resistance and THAT is what RH is about. 
7. So you may think me telling a story about Jenny Weasley being a candidate for an episode of Maury where the young girl yells, “Imma suck d*ck every day and skip school and do bad stuff with my friends and I hate you mama” has nothing to do with revolution…
8. But frivolous Blk girl joy is a goal. 
9. Writing this book I tried to see it as a standard.
10. I don’t talk abt Harry Potter or romance novels in the book. But they supported me in creating the spaciousness to tell you these truths I’m sharing in the book

So run to preorder my book! And tell me in the comment section how old you were the first time you tied a ngas shoe or chased down a demon for your boo? Cause I’m abt to be 40 in January and still — nope! 😭🤭 www.ebonyjanice.com <- Preorder my book! 🔮🙏🏾

(sigh) I saw @vanlathan on Twitter/a podcast repost asking why y’all won’t read books but keep getting on the World Wide Web saying things like it is a fact? And I just return to my question, “Do people think things through?” I won’t say people don’t think… but I think people arrive at a thought and trust it like it’s the power of the Holy Ghost! Non, mes amis! You have to take the thought you thunk and think it — through! 

Here is some help in thinking through…
- What is the lineage of my thought? (Where did it come from? What was happening before I thought this? Etc)
- Was I in conversation with anyone before this thought? If so, what makes their contribution credible? (Decolonize credible and just ask — who is this person in conversation with and are they credible AND what is the source material that offers this as credible? Doesn’t have to be a book — but 9/10 somebody somewhere has written abt this not new thing you may think you thought before anyone else… Then check their sources as well to see who they’re thinking with or learning from. This is easy <- Who do they cite? Always a good way to process citation further is to ask have any black women/femmes been in relationship with this thought or have any indigenous folk been in relationship with this thought?)
- Who does it benefit for you to think this thought? - Xan West taught me this easy little trick of how to discard a biased or anti/somebody thought quickly.
- Plainly, is this thought harmful?
- Is there any inter generational citation involved (meaning — who BEFORE this moment has been building foundation for this thought —
ie, waves of womanist/Blk feminist thought)
- Read books and read the people they mention in the footnotes “Do you fools listen to music or do you just skim through it?” - Jay Z
…….
Mbook “All The Black Girls Are Activists” gives deep, loving care to thinking through a thought, Intellectual lineage and how N O B O D Y on this planet can do the deep work of uncovering the foundation of their personal movements for liberation without crediting Blk women and femmes. So yeah - preorder my book www.ebonyjanice.com #AllTheBlackGirlsAreActivists

I had gin. He had bourbon.
I had beef tartare. He had caviar.
I had blue crab spaghetti. He had risotto. I had steak. He had veal. I had chocolate and espresso and ice cream. He had a caramel gelato.

We giggled our way back to my room at The Langham and by the time we entered, the lights and both sides of the bed had been turned down and my “Sexy Sex” playlist was looping to Jhene Aiko’s “Come On.” I swear I didn’t make this request. The service at The Langham on 5th is really that good. 🤷🏾‍♀️

It was one of my favorite dates w/him. It was also the last “official” date we ever had b/c making out on Rachel Cargle’s couch while she was in Jamaica and I was being fass under her mistletoe in Brooklyn doesn’t really count as a date 😉. But everything about his love was worth it.

I manifested him. A best friend. A generous soul. A truth teller. One of the most sovereign beings I have ever met.

He woo’d me with weirdness, crystal clarity and really really good kissing. Only ever “cool” when we were having serious conversations about our hearts. Otherwise he would say things like, “If you’re doing xyz you make me wanna be doing x^2 y^2z^2!” 🫣😂 I do not regret him at all. A yr later my 🖤 broke into pieces when we were both randomly in Paris & he told me he was moving back home to Mali for good. I told him, “If you’re a bird I wanna be a bird too.” But we kissed and stared longingly into our last goodbye on the corner of Rue Saint Dominique and I cried myself to sleep for weeks because a love that big deserves my best dramatics.

Oh happy dagger! 

I’ve been working on closing portals on all the timelines where we end up together. The ones where our love drips over into this timeline in which I have (to) let him go. And I am. I have.

But I am looking forward to the sweetness of what is next because I am not the kind of woman who levels up - I level OUT. And what comes after Jean-Claude? 😏 I wanna know. 
—
One of the ppl that supported me through this beautiful love journey who ensured my heart stayed soft and open and I didn’t miss a thing was @alexandraroxo. She’s opening up her books for 13 ppl in 2023 and I very very recommend her. Chk the link in her bio!❤️

Citation is an ethical issue.
Cite your sources. 
“The spark deserves citation.” - EbonyJanice
Cite spirit if that’s where it came from. 
.
.
.
Citation is a spiritual practice. It brings in your community, your elders, your “intellectual lineage” (Monyee, Haydar 2019) just by saying their names.
.
.
.
“I promise you, if you take even 10 minutes to dig into the archives, you’ll be humbled enough to know you are rarely “the first” anything...” - @/notnikyatu, Twitter 2022)
Lastly, and “I know you girls like to tussle.” (khaenotbae, T!kt0k, 2021) but cite black womens and femmes. Often and with deep intention… otherwise even with all yr cis het male sources you still not credible. And that’s on “the politics of citation” (Richard Delgado). 
——-
Oh! And cite EVERYTIME!!!!! People entering the conversation today didn’t see your first citation in 2017 on Tumblr. Lift the name of your sources in EVERYYYYYY discussion. 
.
.
.
Mkay? 
Ok!

I was in Kwabenya, Ghana this time last year - and it was the most gorgeous time. And then I got a message, while there, that made it the most awful time. And I was sitting there in that gorgeous time and that awful time and I started sobbing and laughing, simultaneously. And I looked up at the sky and said, “Life. You Raggedy Bitch.” Actually, I said “raggely” but for the sake of cross cultural comprehension — LIFE YOU RAGGEDY BITCH!

Cause life be so good.
And life be so awful.

And it just don’t take turns. Oh no... same day it be amazing, something awful sitting there looking at you like... “Hey Lil Ashy Girl. I got something for you.”

Then same day it be ugly - something spectacular skipping through the house like, “Come here my love - and this and this and this too.”

And so I have learned that you gotta have deep ritual. Not like wait til’ you get to the altar on Sunday morning ritual. Like - you gon’ have to build an altar at your house and go lay there daily (twice a day... sometimes thrice) cause LIFE!

And any theology that keeps you from ritual where you get to love yourself deeply, grieve your lungs dry, scream your skin raw, and relish in the deep hollows of your heart that makes you beautiful and sincere is not a theology worth preaching. More and more I ask myself, “Why did it take me so long to trust that God could love me here where everything aint cute and there is no bright side of this story
.
.
.
.
until there is.”

— 
EbonyJanice.Is.Watching.God.
#TheEbonyJaniceProject

Before I ever studied leadership or education in a formal or organized manner I knew my mothers were leaders. You have heard me say that I basically had 7 moms. My Grandmother has 6 daughters and we had such a village experience growing up that you could drop a child off at Grandmas house and not even call in advance. Grandma had a big house but one bathroom and I do not have a memory of the lock on that bathroom door ever working. We were close. 
😬
But I was raised in an “all things in common” manner. Including wisdom. When I got my B.A. my cousin Emmico said, “We graduated.” Do you understand what I mean when I say - everything is everyone’s even your brilliance?
💜
Our mothers imbued is with the power to be leaders. I was made to get longer Easter speeches. I was taught how to create lesson plans to teach Sunday school at a young age. I was made to sit at the table and help younger cousins with their homework. Everything was everyone’s.
🙏🏾
At our mothers hands we were taught that leading was a natural phenomenon. Before we had language for what #Womanism was we were living out Womanist principles. “When you educate a woman, you educate the nation” because “You Celie and I’m Nettie. If I know it you will know it too.”
📖
“All The Black Girls Are Activists: a 4th Wave Womanists Pursuit Of Dreams As radical Résistance” is my attempt at sharing a thing I know in my bones that you may already know - but I’m here to reinforce. Womanist = Womanish.
While there are negative connotations in relation to the idea of a black girl being “womanish” or “grown” (read: Fast|Fass), Womanist|Womanist behavior predates matriarchate slavery tropes of the black woman as “#mammy” or “mother.” The *communal nature of black girlhood (emphasis on the cross-cultural shared experience of black girlhood not specifically the definition of black girls’ being) before, during, after and still since slavery is a major part of why black women’s living is #intersectional womanism, inherently. However, if we emphasize the necessity of “mothering” a community as a result of separation from birth continent and family due to chattel slavery, those of us here in America, as direct descendants of chattel slavery can intimately relate to being “womanish” in the sense of “taking care of others before we were old enough to even take care of ourselves. This is both a gift and a curse of an inheritance because black women tend to have a deep relationship with production and labor as indicators of their value. 
—
Read #AngelaDavis’ essay, “Role of Black Women in the Community of Slaves” as a way to deepen your understanding of where many of the gender based personifications and race-based stereotypes of black women in America come from.

Read the “Girlhood Interrupted: The erasure Of Black girls childhood” to learn more about the intentional ways Blk girls are adultified. 

Preorder my contribution to womanist thought - “All The Black Girls Are Activists: a 4th Wave Womanists Pursuit Of Dreams As Radical Resistance” to learn more abt the ways I see Black girls as worthy of more than just holding all the strength and wisdom for the world! Www.ebonyjanice.com

I always like to note the unlikely hood that Sojourner Truth ever specifically said the words, “Ain’t I A Woman” while drinking her juice in the hood… but nevertheless, the jist of what we can confirm and believe Sister Truth was saying is, “There was no black women’s slave work and black men’s slave work. We were doing the same work. PLUS I was birthing babies and dealing with Massa’s (redacted) so 😬 how is there a separation of us today I’m getting our rights?” And to the great care all ppl seemed to have for white women she was saying, “Ain’t nobody ever treated me gently or helped me over no puddle like white women. But I am a woman too. Ain’t I?” | Current medical practices, policies and support around reproductive issues, incarceration rates, and the ways Little BLK girls are treated in school would prove that this treatment and trope lives on.
.
.
.
So I wrote “All The Black Girls Are Activists: a 4th Wave Womanists Pursuit Of Dreams As Radical Resistance” (which you shld preorder today at www.ebonyjanice.com - links for several online outlets on the ATBGAA page) because I wanted to talk about a soft place from which Black Women and Girls deserve to exist. Defining softness beyond the Blk Twitter timeline aesthetic and using the elders and ancestral wisdom to prove that my vulnerability and cocreating safe space for other Blk femmes to be vulnerable is revolutionary work! 
.
.

I recently saw a video by Dr. Nokuthula Hlabangoane where she started off by talking about how black thought needs to be at the center of our (black) thinking. That immediately made me think of how people have created labels, titles, tropes, stereotypes, caricatures of us since time and it becomes a radical form of resistance for us to say, “This is what I call me.” Before Alice Walker fleshed out her definition of “womanist” in “In Search of Our Mothers Gardens” she has mentioned it in a response to a book review that basically said, “at the very least we should be able to name ourselves.’ When Black women are not at the center of defining themselves (or writing abt themselves) they will always be defined by biased, often racist persons who are creating their truths based on that racism and bias. No... at the very least I shld be able to name myself!
.
.
.
When I wrote “All The Black Girls Are Activists: a 4th Wave Womanists Pursuit Of Dreams As radical résistance” I wrote it as a way to NAME ourselves. In fact there’s a whole chapter on the importance of naming and a whole paragraph full of the names of the Black women whose platonic love for me is so deep they are my soul mates, my best friends, my business partners, my collaborators… my all. And I would choose that relationship type over every relationship because Black women who love me deep make me so seen and safe! If the world understood this kind of safety and seeing we (Black women) would be freer and freer! 

Preorder #alltheblackgirlsareactivists at ebonyjanice.com today and then follow that hashtag as we learn more abt Womanism so you are at an intro level of knowing by the time the book comes out in a few short months!

I remember when Dr. su’ad abdul khabeer said, “You don’t need to be a voice for the voiceless, just pass the mic” and I wanted to send her an offering, a tithe, and episcopal support because that is the gospel by which I believe all people should live their lives. That is womanism at it’s best. It’s the reason why I say womanism is inherently intersectional because our living is about making sure that “the least of these” are served and seen and if we hear from them we are enlarged and expanded because we know what the majority thinks (and that has rarely advanced us) so let’s be available for what those who have been disabled, maligned and marginalized know about surviving and thriving. 
 
All The Black Girls Are Activists: a 4th Wave Womanists Pursuit of dreams as radical resistance is my love letter to Black women and girls. As a daughter of Hip Hop I have learned to not wait for the mic to be passed. We take it.

Before y’all take this out of context - Im not saying you NEVER saw Blk women chilling before - Im saying in this 4th wave of womanist thought/preachment — we have built theory and provided visuals of what that would look like. You don’t have to dig through the archives to find us at rest the way we squeal for delight when we find photos of Rosa Parks doing yoga, Toni Morrison dancing at a book release or Nikki Giovanni lounging on her couch. The work of 4th wave womanism brings us active theory (and language) to know what that squeal is about: a longing for softness (which I’ve defined and cited the origin of this language in All The Black Girls Are Activists) and our longing for some chilling Black women. 
.
.
.
On my quest to continue introducing you to womanism - I’ll take this moment to share about Black Liberation Theology. * Black Liberation Theology is what Dr. James Cone says, “a rational study of the being of God in the world in light of the existential situation of an e oppressed community, relating the forces of liberation to the essence of the Gospel, which is Jesus Christ.” Black theology mixes Christianity with questions of civil rights, particularly raised by the Black Power movement.” Womanist *Theology emerged from within this work because black women realized that, similar to other movements for justice within the black community, BLT had no emphasis on the impact on black womens unique experience as both black and woman.
One of my favorite theologians, Xan West once suggested we always ask of sacred text, “Who does it benefit for me to believe it this way?” THAT is how we can incorporate Womanist Theology into our life! Who benefits most from believing what you believe? If it is not the poor and disenfranchised — it ain’t a belief worth believing!

It only matter that the blood he shed for all of us was red.”Me:  That’s a lovely poem you shared there. But if it doesn’t matter that, as Kelly Brown Douglas says, “Christ has black skin and black features” why has history, consistently and intentionally, painted him as a white man with white features? I mean, if his red blood is the only thing that actually matters, why is he so grossly and inaccurately painted as 80’s Brad Pitt Jesus?
